{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a0a54e76-7ef1-4e09-a52c-c79a17e73b42","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's Security.framework **never natively supported DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, a managed/OpenSSL-backed shim provided DSA on macOS. .NET 11 removed that shim — `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on all Apple platforms (macOS, iOS, tvOS). Windows and Linux are unaffected because they have native DSA support (CNG and OpenSSL respectively).\n\nThis follows the broader .NET trend of dropping legacy algorithms that the host OS doesn't support natively.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have two options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for verify-only)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Convert your existing key/signature to BouncyCastle types\nISigner signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\nsigner.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\nThis is fully managed code — no platform dependency at all.\n\n### Option 2 — Guard with a runtime check\n\nIf you want to keep using the built-in `DSA` class on platforms that support it:\n\n```csharp\nstatic bool IsDsaSupported()\n{\n    try { using var _ = DSA.Create(); return true; }\n    catch (PlatformNotSupportedException) { return false; }\n}\n```\n\nThen fall back to BouncyCastle on macOS.\n\n### Long-term recommendation\n\nDSA is a **legacy algorithm** (FIPS 186-4 recommends ECDSA or EdDSA). If possible, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **RSA** and retire the DSA code paths entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8b91ddfe-fa9b-45ba-a727-8f4671976a50","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, and more significantly in later versions, .NET has been deprecating and removing support for older cryptographic algorithms on certain platforms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7+, DSA on macOS was already problematic because macOS's native crypto library (Apple's CryptoKit/Security framework) doesn't support DSA. Previously, .NET used OpenSSL on macOS for DSA operations, but there have been changes.\n \nThe specific issue is that in .NET 7, `DSA` on macOS throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` because Apple's Security framework doesn't support DSA, and .NET stopped relying on OpenSSL for these operations on macOS. But the user says it worked on .NET 10 and broke on .NET 11, so I need to figure out what changed between those versions specifically. on what's actually documented about DSA support across .NET versions, since the specific version boundary matters less than understanding the underlying platform limitation that drives these changes.\n\nThe core issue is that Apple's native crypto frameworks don't support DSA, so .NET has been removing its managed fallback implementations. If someone needs to work with legacy DSA signatures, they'd need to either use a third-party library like BouncyCastle, call OpenSSL directly through interop, or ideally migrate to RSA or ECDSA instead.","outputTokens":1393,"requestId":"886B:A067E:1D6048D:20D4B79:69FA9D2E"},"id":"2ac65da1-eedf-4889-983e-052f65e9b346","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:45:50.646Z","parentId":"a0260857-e5d2-4ab7-b494-fce66eedafd5"}
